{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f4fef5ff-2a58-48bb-b5b9-7a75d6685ad7","content":"On macOS, the OS automatically generates **`.ips` crash reports** when a process crashes. You don't need `createdump`.\n\n**Where to find them:**\n\n- **User crashes:** `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`\n- **System crashes:** `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`\n\nLook for files named like `YourAppName-YYYY-MM-DD-HHMMSS.ips`.\n\n**To view:**\n```bash\n# List recent crash reports\nls -lt ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/*.ips | head\n\n# Or open Console.app → Crash Reports\nopen -a Console\n```\n\n**For core dumps** (if you need a full memory dump), enable them with:\n```bash\nulimit -c unlimited\n```\nThen reproduce the crash — the core file appears in `/cores/`.\n\n> **Tip:** The `.ips` crash log contains the native backtrace with unsymbolicated frames. If you need to symbolicate .NET runtime frames (e.g., `libcoreclr.so`), I can help with that using the **apple-crash-symbolication** skill.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"dbb3e634-a48a-4857-b6a8-9024321bd675","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, without createdump. This is a knowledge question — I don't need to search the codebase or run tools. Let me answer directly.","outputTokens":345,"requestId":"6087:250B0D:2C9B0F:3A4812:69FFE3D5"},"id":"e60d4f4f-438e-4f34-bfb4-23e6e07284cb","timestamp":"2026-05-10T01:48:15.086Z","parentId":"3879f2fc-b677-4fc6-999a-7522c5a095d6"}
